{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18669"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18669"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.28,0.13,0.14,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1578"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"2524"},{"type":"tags","id":"2573"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41613"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive exertional dyspnoea over six months. He reports worsening breathlessness when lying flat. He has no chest pain, cough, or leg swelling. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history who quit five years ago. He underwent coronary artery bypass surgery eight years ago. He has iron deficiency anaemia for which he takes oral iron supplements. His other medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, and metoprolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals reduced breath sounds at the left base. Heart sounds are normal with no added sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest radiograph shows an elevated left hemidiaphragm and apical emphysaematous changes. Pulmonary function tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal Lung Capacity: 4.2 L (65% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForced Vital Capacity: 2.8 L (70% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForced Expiratory Volume in one second: 2.3 L (75% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1/FVC ratio: 82%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiffusion Capacity for Carbon Monoxide: 16 mL/min/mmHg (65% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransfer Coefficient (KCO): 98% predicted\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron deficiency anaemia","Pulmonary fibrosis","Left pleural effusion","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Left hemidiaphragm paralysis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of left hemidiaphragm paralysis, including exertional dyspnoea, orthopnoea, and characteristic radiological and pulmonary function findings. The condition often occurs following cardiac surgery due to phrenic nerve injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft hemidiaphragm paralysis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with this constellation of findings: elevated hemidiaphragm on chest radiograph, restrictive pattern on pulmonary function tests (reduced TLC and FVC), but importantly, a preserved KCO despite reduced DLCO. This pattern occurs because the reduced gas transfer is proportional to the reduced lung volume, indicating no intrinsic problem with the alveolar-capillary membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dyspnoea but would not explain the elevated hemidiaphragm on chest radiograph or the restrictive pattern on pulmonary function tests. While anaemia does reduce DLCO (due to fewer haemoglobin molecules being available to bind carbon monoxide), it characteristically preserves KCO as the reduction in DLCO is proportional to the reduction in haemoglobin concentration. Therefore, while this patient\u0027s anaemia may be contributing to his reduced DLCO, it cannot explain his full clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E would show a restrictive pattern but with reduced KCO due to impaired gas transfer across damaged alveolar-capillary membranes. Additionally, chest radiograph would show reticular or honeycomb changes rather than an elevated hemidiaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E would show blunting of the costophrenic angle and possibly a meniscus sign on chest radiograph, rather than a smooth elevated hemidiaphragm. Breath sounds would be absent rather than just reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease\u003C/strong\u003E would show an obstructive pattern on pulmonary function tests with reduced FEV1/FVC ratio, rather than the restrictive pattern seen here. The chest radiograph would typically show hyperinflation rather than an elevated hemidiaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unilateral diaphragm paralysis typically presents with dyspnoea and orthopnoea, with characteristic elevation of the hemidiaphragm on chest radiograph.","Pulmonary function tests in diaphragm paralysis show a restrictive pattern with preserved KCO, distinguishing it from parenchymal lung disease.","Anaemia reduces DLCO but preserves KCO as there are fewer haemoglobin molecules available for CO binding."],"references":["Kokatnur L, Rudrappa M. Diaphragmatic palsy. Diseases. 2018 Feb 13;6(1):16.","Qureshi A. Diaphragm paralysis. InSeminars in respiratory and critical care medicine 2009 Jun (Vol. 30, No. 03, pp. 315-320). \u00a9 Thieme Medical Publishers."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18669"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T14:07:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T14:08:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76726"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"